======================================================================
PART 2: FIBONACCI {2,3} DECOMPOSITION OF EDGES
======================================================================

  The Zeckendorf representation uses Fibonacci numbers (sums of {1,2}).
  A PADOVAN-like decomposition uses {2,3}:

    m = 2a + 3b (how many ways?)

  For the tournament edge set of size m = n(n-1)/2:
    n=3: m=3 = 3×1 + 2×0  or  2×0+3×1
    n=4: m=6 = 2×3 + 3×0  or  2×0+3×2
    n=5: m=10 = 2×5 + 3×0 or 2×2+3×2 or 2×0+3×... no, 10/3 not integer
    n=6: m=15 = 2×0+3×5 or 2×3+3×3 or 2×6+3×1
    n=7: m=21 = 3×7 + 2×0  or ...

  This {2,3} decomposition counts: floor(m/2) - max(0, ceil((m-3*floor(m/3))/2)) + 1

  More interestingly: PAIR the arcs! Each arc has a "partner" via the
  common vertex structure. Two arcs sharing a vertex = ADJACENT.
  Non-adjacent arcs (disjoint endpoints) = INDEPENDENT.


  n=3: m=3
    (2, 3)-decompositions of m: 1
      0×2 + 1×3 = 3  (uses 1 blocks covering 3 edges)
    m mod 3 = 0, m mod 6 = 3

  n=4: m=6
    (2, 3)-decompositions of m: 2
      3×2 + 0×3 = 6  (uses 3 blocks covering 6 edges)
      0×2 + 2×3 = 6  (uses 2 blocks covering 6 edges)
    m mod 3 = 0, m mod 6 = 0

  n=5: m=10
    (2, 3)-decompositions of m: 2
      5×2 + 0×3 = 10  (uses 5 blocks covering 10 edges)
      2×2 + 2×3 = 10  (uses 4 blocks covering 10 edges)
    m mod 3 = 1, m mod 6 = 4

  n=6: m=15
    (2, 3)-decompositions of m: 3
      6×2 + 1×3 = 15  (uses 7 blocks covering 15 edges)
      3×2 + 3×3 = 15  (uses 6 blocks covering 15 edges)
      0×2 + 5×3 = 15  (uses 5 blocks covering 15 edges)
    m mod 3 = 0, m mod 6 = 3

  n=7: m=21
    (2, 3)-decompositions of m: 4
      9×2 + 1×3 = 21  (uses 10 blocks covering 21 edges)
      6×2 + 3×3 = 21  (uses 9 blocks covering 21 edges)
      3×2 + 5×3 = 21  (uses 8 blocks covering 21 edges)
      0×2 + 7×3 = 21  (uses 7 blocks covering 21 edges)
    m mod 3 = 0, m mod 6 = 3

  m mod 6 for n=3..20:
    n=3: m=3, m mod 6 = 3  * divisible by 3
    n=4: m=6, m mod 6 = 0  *** divisible by 6!
